sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1725429
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The regulator comes from the genomic sequence of the unicellular cyanobacterium Synechocystis sp. PCC6803.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The UV intensity response regulator coding sequence was positioned downstream of J23116, a constitutive promoter family member, and upstream of the double terminator B0015. This allows the part to be placed in front of other parts with weaker or non-constitutive promoters.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The regulator and J23101 were ligated to B0015 after restriction that was followed by an Azure-A-based gel extraction.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andrey Filipov

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0015
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Double terminator consisting of BBa_B0010 and BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1725425
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The regulator comes from the genomic sequence of the unicellular cyanobacterium Synechocystis sp. PCC6803.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The UV intensity response regulator coding sequence was placed downstream of J23116, a constitutive promoter family member.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The regulator was ligated to J23116 (which came in the form of an annealed oligo) after restriction that was followed by an Azure-A-based gel extraction.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andrey Filipov

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0010
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional terminator consisting of a 64 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1725421
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: UirR comes from the genomic sequence of the unicellular cyanobacterium Synechocystis sp. PCC6803.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The regulator (K1725420) that participates together with PlsiR (K1725400) and UirS (K1725410) to activate a response to UV-A light has been put downstream of the RBS B0032.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Due to the length of the DNA sequence, the gene was amplified via PCR and the BioBrick suffix and prefix, alongside with the RBS, were added as part of the primers. The last base of the gene was changed from G to A because different stop codons can be more efficient in different species and TAA is especially efficient in E. coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andrey Filipov

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0032
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Weak1 RBS based on Ron Weiss thesis. Strength is considered relative to <bb_part>BBa_B0030</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0031</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0033</bb_part>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix ("RBS-2" in figure 4-14 of thesis).

Contact info for this part: Brian Chow
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: UirR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The regulator comes from the genomic sequence of the unicellular cyanobacterium Synechocystis sp. PCC6803
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: UirR is a protein that attaches itself to the transmembrane protein UirS (K1725410). After exposure to unidirectional UV-A, UirS releases UirR, which physically interacts with the lsiR promoter (K1725400), activating transcription. All three parts are required for a cell to respond to the UV-A stimulus.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Due to the length of the DNA sequence, the gene was amplified via PCR and the BioBrick suffix and prefix were added as part of the primers. The last base of the gene was changed from G to A because different stop codons can be more efficient in different species and TAA is especially efficient in E. coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andrey Filipov
